# ECS

## Core concepts

| Concept | Role | Lives in |
|---------|------|----------|
| **Entity** | Plain bag of components; no methods | Game `createXEntity()` factories |
| **Component** | Data-only plain object | `viberanium/components/` or game `components/` |
| **System** | `installXSystem(registry, ...deps)` — one concern per installer | `viberanium/src/systems/` or game `systems/` |
| **Scene** | Owns a scene `Registry`; load/unload level content | Game `scenes/` |
| **Game** | Owns persistent game `Registry` + active scene | `bootstrap.ts` |

## Entity assembly

Entities are built by game factories, then registered by the scene:

```typescript
const entity = registry.createBare();
entity.components[COMPONENT_KEYS.transform] = createTransform();
entity.components[COMPONENT_KEYS.character] = createCharacterController();
entity.components[COMPONENT_KEYS.movementIntent] = createMovementIntent();
entity.components[PLAYER_CONTROLLER_KEY] = createPlayerController();
registry.register(entity);
```

Mesh sub-entities are allowed only for static props (`renderGroup`) until props migrate to `meshDraws`. Skeletal body meshes live on the character entity via `meshDraws.parts[]`.

## Hierarchy components

| Component | Role |
|-----------|------|
| `childOf` | `{ parentId }` — explicit parent link |
| `children` | `{ ids[] }` — maintained on parent at spawn/despawn |
| `localTransform` | position/yaw/scale relative to parent (non-bone children) |
| `boneAttachment` | bone index + local offset + attach scene on child entities |
| `meshDraws` | GPU mesh parts on the same entity as `skeletalModel` |
| `animationClipMap` | `clips` keyed by `AnimStateId` — state → retargeted clip |
| `animationStateMachine` | current state, timers, playback tuning — not on `character` |

`character` is **physics only** (velocity, gravity, `onGround`, `sliding`, `groundNormal`). Body dims come from the character's `characterCollision`-flagged `collider` children — spawned by `spawnActorColliders` as bone-attached, character-local, or attachment-local entities (never a collider on the character root itself). Bone-attached physics bodies track **bind-pose** bones relative to the character root (not clip-driven crouch). `collectCharacterCollisionColliders` + `readCharacterBodyFromCollisionColliders` resolve those children into a solver cylinder each physics tick; an actor with **zero** colliders resolves to `null` and is skipped entirely — no physics, no movement. Animation timing and blend weights live on `animationStateMachine` and per-clip components.

### CharacterController fields

| Field | Role |
|-------|------|
| `velocity`, `moveSpeed`, `jumpSpeed`, `gravity` | Integration + tuning |
| `onGround` | Walkable floor contact (slope ≤ `floorMaxAngle`) |
| `sliding` | Active slope-slide state (steep box faces) |
| `slideSpeed` | Current downhill slide speed magnitude |
| `groundNormal` | Surface normal when grounded or sliding |
| `floorMaxAngle` | Max walkable slope (default 50°) |
| `obstructiveColliderKeys` | Component keys queried as static obstacles (default `[collider]`) |
| `coyoteRemaining`, `jumpBufferRemaining` | Jump grace windows |

### Collider component

Static props and level geometry use `isStatic: true`. Character body colliders use `isStatic: false` (the mover, not an obstacle). Shapes: `box`, `cylinder`, `sphere`, `ellipsoid`. Authored `localShape` is baked to world `shape` + `aabb` each frame by `installColliderTransformSystem` when `transform.dirty`.

## Component rules

- Data only — no `actions`, no registry imports, no per-frame logic
- Use `COMPONENT_KEYS` constants — never raw string literals for component keys
- Controllers write `movementIntent`; shared systems read it
- **Movement** is the canonical term for character intent — use `movementIntent`; never use `locomotion` in names or docs

## System rules

- One concern per `install*System` — never combine input + physics + animation
- Query the registry each frame — never hold entity references or collider arrays
- Install on the registry that owns the entities (scene registry for level content)

## Controller pattern

Player and AI characters share movement, physics, collision, and animation systems. Only the controller differs:

| Component | Written by | Read by |
|-----------|-----------|---------|
| `playerController` (sandbox) | — (tag) | `installPlayerInputSystem` |
| `testAi` (sandbox) | — (data) | `installTestAiSystem` |
| `movementIntent` | controller systems | `installMovementSystem` |
| `character` | movement + physics | physics, yaw (`installCharacterStateSystem`), animation FSM |
| `collider` (character body/hurtboxes) | spawn (`spawnActorColliders`, bone/character/attachment children) | `collectCharacterCollisionColliders` + `readCharacterBodyFromCollisionColliders` in physics |
| `animationStateMachine` | `installAnimationFsmSystem`, movement jump | pose system |
| `animationClipMap` | spawn from character def | pose system |
| `navGrid` | — (data, `dirty` flag) | `installNavGridSystem` (rebuild when dirty), `installTestAiSystem` |

## Registry queries

```typescript
for (const e of registry.view(COMPONENT_KEYS.character)) { ... }

const colliders = registry.getComponentsByName(COMPONENT_KEYS.collider) as Collider[];
```

- `view(key)` — cached entity list for one component key
- `getComponentsByName(key)` — flat list of all component instances (collision, raycasts)
- Never pass collider arrays or entity references to system installers

## Component lifecycle

```typescript
registry.addComponent(entity, COMPONENT_KEYS.collider, collider);
registry.removeComponent(entity, COMPONENT_KEYS.collider);
registry.deregister(entity.id);
```

`addComponent` / `removeComponent` invalidate the view cache for that key.

## Scene boundaries

- **Game registry** — persistent entities (render pipeline draw action, scene manager, global input handlers)
- **Scene registry** — ephemeral; one per active level visit
- `scene.load()` creates all level content including the nav grid entity
- `scene.unload()` disposes skeletal systems (GPU pose pass), then deregisters **all** entities (including nav grid and ground) — nothing persists on the registry
- `game.setActiveScene(null)` drops the active scene; the `Scene` object is discarded after `switchTo` completes
- Frame loop runs game registry actions first, then active scene registry actions
- Construct **level editor** placements use editor tags (`editableTarget`, level placement) without playable `testAi` / player — playable spawn remains sandbox `useLevelScene`

## Character collision

CPU cylinder move-and-slide in `viberanium/collision/` — pure math, no registry. Gameplay uses `installCharacterPhysicsSystem`; optional GPU resolve (`installCollisionSystem`) is exported but **not installed** in sandbox.

### Module layout

| File | Role |
|------|------|
| `collision/characterContact.ts` | Capsule-vs-shape narrowphase, box top queries, footprint overlap |
| `collision/characterCollision.ts` | Contact classification, floor snap (skipped while ascending), wall slide, slope slide, `resolveCylinderMoveAndSlide` |
| `collision/collisionBroadphase.ts` | 64×64 spatial grid for static colliders |
| `collision/characterCollisionBody.ts` | Walk a character's `characterCollision` colliders (own + bone/attachment children) into a solver `CharacterBodyCylinder` |
| `systems/colliderTransformSystem.ts` | Bake `localShape` → world `shape` |
| `systems/movementSystem.ts` | Intent → velocity; ground-plane projection; blocks input while sliding |
| `systems/characterPhysicsSystem.ts` | Gravity, substep integrate, broadphase query, resolve, slide speed |
| `systems/characterStateSystem.ts` | Yaw toward intent — skipped while sliding |
| `spawn/spawnActorColliders.ts` | Spawns every `ActorColliderDef` as a child entity (bone-attached, character-local, or attachment-local) carrying its own `collider` |
| `systems/combat/installHitboxFollowSystem.ts` | Bone-attached + nested collider follow: `characterCollision` bodies use bind-pose bone × character root (cached model offset); combat hitboxes/hurtboxes sample animated clips; chain mask excludes collision bodies |

### Pipeline

```
Controllers → movementIntent
  → hitboxFollow (8): bake bone/nested collider worlds (bind body + animated hitboxes)
  → movementSystem (8): desiredVelocity → velocity; project onto groundNormal when onGround
  → colliderTransformSystem (8): static collider world bake
  → characterPhysicsSystem (9–10): integrate → resolveCylinderMoveAndSlide → onGround/sliding/groundNormal
  → hitboxFollow (11): re-glue after physics moves the character root
  → characterStateSystem (13): yaw (skipped when sliding)
```

Broadphase candidates come from `getNearbyObstacles(registry, character.obstructiveColliderKeys, x, z, radius)`. `markNavGridDirty` also invalidates the collision broadphase.

### Jump while ascending / embedded

`resolveCylinderMoveAndSlide` does **not** ground-plane snap or set `onGround` from walkable floors while `velocity[1] > 0`. Jumping works when the body is flush with or slightly embedded in a floor; upward velocity is preserved. `trySurfaceSnap` stays gated on `vy ≤ 0` or already grounded.

### Ramps (no dedicated type)

There is **no `ramp` component or identifier**. Ramps are **rotated box colliders** — prop colliders, level `composition.colliders` placements, or Construct-authored geometry with non-identity rotation. Slope behavior is angle-based via contact normals:

| Slope angle (from horizontal) | Classification | Behavior |
|-------------------------------|----------------|----------|
| 0°–`floorMaxAngle` (default 50°) | Walkable floor | `onGround`; movement projected onto `groundNormal` |
| `floorMaxAngle`–80° (`SLIDE_MAX_ANGLE`) | Slide slope | `sliding`; downhill auto-velocity; input suppressed |
| > 80° | Wall | Blocked; wall-slide velocity projection |

### Two kinds of "slide"

| Kind | Mechanism | State |
|------|-----------|-------|
| **Slope slide** | `character.sliding` + `applySlideVelocity` on steep box faces | Persistent until walkable floor or jump cancel |
| **Wall slide** | `slideVelocityOnWall` strips velocity into walls during resolve | No persistent state |

Slope slide starts when landing on or hitting a 50°–80° box face while airborne. `slideSpeed` ramps from `moveSpeed × SLIDE_START_SPEED_FACTOR` to `moveSpeed × SLIDE_MAX_SPEED_FACTOR`. Jump during slide coyote cancels sliding. `animationStateMachine` treats sliding as grounded (no run anim).

### Ground plane

`readGroundPlaneY(registry)` reads the infinite horizontal floor from the `groundPlane` entity — separate from prop/box colliders. Resolver snaps feet to this Y when below it **and not ascending** (`velocity[1] ≤ 0`).

## Nav grid

The nav grid is a first-class scene component — not a hidden cache inside an AI system.

| Piece | Location | Role |
|-------|----------|------|
| `NavGridComponent` | `viberanium/components/navGrid.ts` | Grid bounds, `blocked` cells, `agentRadius`, `dirty` flag |
| `createNavGrid()` | component factory | Allocates grid data; `dirty` starts `true` |
| `markNavGridDirty(registry)` | component helper | Sets `dirty = true` after collider changes during an active level |
| `updateNavGridBlocked()` | `viberanium/navigation/navGrid.ts` | Pure rebuild of `blocked` from static colliders |
| `installNavGridSystem()` | `viberanium/systems/navGridSystem.ts` | Rebuilds only when `dirty`; clears flag after rebuild |
| `findPath` / `pickRandomObjective` | `viberanium/navigation/astar.ts` | Read the grid; never build or own one |

### Lifecycle

Nav grid entity is registered in `scene.load()` and deregistered in `scene.unload()` alongside props and NPCs. Only the active level holds a grid in memory.

```typescript
// inside scene.load()
const navGridEntity = registry.createBare();
navGridEntity.components[COMPONENT_KEYS.navGrid] = createNavGrid(navGridConfig);
registry.register(navGridEntity);
```

Bounds come from `LevelDefinition.navGrid` in the level catalog.

### Dirty rebuild contract

- **Do not** rebuild the nav grid every update — only when `navGrid.dirty` is true
- **Do** call `markNavGridDirty(registry)` when static colliders are added or removed during an active level (e.g. `instantiateProp`, runtime destructibles)
- AI systems read the scene grid via `registry.view(COMPONENT_KEYS.navGrid)` — never build or cache their own grid
- Nav grid blocking uses XZ footprint overlap only — **no slope-angle awareness**; any static collider footprint blocks the cell

## Forbidden

- Monolithic systems combining input, physics, and animation
- `registry.view('character')[0]` in bootstrap to wire a specific entity
- Bootstrap-time `staticColliders: Collider[]` arrays passed to systems
- Behavior logic inside component factories
- Per-frame nav grid rebuilds without `dirty`
- AI-owned nav grid caches (`WeakMap<Registry, NavGrid>`) — the scene component is the single source of truth
- Persistent nav grid entities across `unload()` — grid is level content, destroyed with the level
- `locomotion` in any identifier, filename, or doc text
- `rigRenderMeshes`, `rigOwner`, `skeletalAnimations` blobs, shared `Transform` refs across entities
- Orphan render sub-entities for skeletal body meshes — use `meshDraws` on the logic entity
- Monolithic `installSkeletalAnimationSystem` — use `installSkeletalCharacterSystems`
- `ramp` as a component type, collider kind, or identifier — use rotated box colliders
- Installing both `installCharacterPhysicsSystem` and `installCollisionSystem` on the same scene registry
- Collision math that imports registry or systems — keep it in `viberanium/collision/`
